"Rodríguez-Serrano E., Navas C.A., Bozinovic F.","The comparative field body temperature among Liolaemus lizards: Testing the static and the labile hypotheses",2009,"Journal of Thermal Biology","34","6",,"306","309",,,10.1016/j.jtherbio.2009.04.002,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-68649126528&partnerID=40&md5=76e5b28da104f86143f9d5f444142dd1","Center for Advanced Studies in Ecology and Biodiversity (CASEB), LINC-Global, Departamento de Ecología, Santiago, 6513677, Chile; Departamento de Fisiología, Instituto de Biociências, Universidade de São Paulo, Rua do Matão Tr. 14, No. 321, CEP 05508-900 São Paulo, SP, Brazil","Rodríguez-Serrano, E., Center for Advanced Studies in Ecology and Biodiversity (CASEB), LINC-Global, Departamento de Ecología, Santiago, 6513677, Chile; Navas, C.A., Departamento de Fisiología, Instituto de Biociências, Universidade de São Paulo, Rua do Matão Tr. 14, No. 321, CEP 05508-900 São Paulo, SP, Brazil; Bozinovic, F., Center for Advanced Studies in Ecology and Biodiversity (CASEB), LINC-Global, Departamento de Ecología, Santiago, 6513677, Chile","Two competing hypotheses have been suggested to explain thermal sensitivity of lizards to environmental conditions. These are the static and the labile hypotheses. The static hypothesis posits that thermal physiology is evolutionary conservative and consequently relatively insensitive to directional selection. Contrarily, the labile hypothesis states that thermal physiology does respond readily to directional selection in some lizard taxa. In this paper, we tested both hypotheses among species of Liolaemus lizards. The genus Liolaemus is diverse with about 200 species, being broadly distributed from central Perú to Tierra del Fuego at the southern end of South America. Data of field body temperature (Tb) from Liolaemus species were collected from the literature. Based on the distributional range of the species we also collected data of mean annual ambient temperatures. We observed that both the traditional analysis and the phylogenetic approach indicate that in the genus Liolaemus Tb of species varies in a manner that is consistent with ecological gradient of ambient temperature. The data suggest that the thermal physiology of Liolaemus lizards is evolutionarily flexible, and that this plasticity has been partially responsible for the colonization of a wide array of thermal environments. © 2009 Elsevier Ltd. All rights reserved.","Global warming; Liolaemus lizards; South America; Thermoregulation","article; body temperature; ecology; environmental factor; lizard; nonhuman; phylogeny; South America; species diversity; temperature sensitivity; thermoregulation; Liolaemus; Squamata",,,,,,"Angilletta, M.J., Niewiarowski, P.E., Navas, C.A., The evolution of thermal physiology in ectotherms (2002) J. Therm. Biol., 27, pp. 249-268; Bogert, C.M., Thermoregulation in reptiles, a factor in evolution (1949) Evolution, 3, pp. 195-211; Bozinovic, F., Rosenmann, M., Maximum metabolic rate of rodents: physiological and ecological consequences on distributional limits (1989) Funct. Ecol., 3, pp. 173-181; Calosi, P., Bilton, D.T., Spicer, J.I., Thermal tolerance, acclimatory capacity and vulnerability to global climate change (2008) Biol. Lett., 4, pp. 99-102; Carothers, J.H., Fox, S.F., Marquet, P.A., Jaksic, F.M., Thermal characteristics of ten Andean lizards of the genus Liolaemus in central Chile (1997) Rev. Chil. His. Nat., 70, pp. 297-309; Carothers, J.H., Jaksic, F.M., Marquet, P.A., Altitudinal zonation among lizards of the genus Liolaemus: questions answered and unanswered questions (2001) Rev. Chil. Hist. Nat., 74, pp. 313-316; Carothers, J.H., Marquet, P.A., Jaksic, F.M., Thermal ecology of a Liolaemus lizard assemblage along an Andean altitudinal gradient in Chile (1998) Rev. Chil. Hist. Nat., 71, pp. 39-50; Cowles, R.B., Bogert, C.M., A preliminary study of the thermal requirements of desert reptiles (1944) Bull. Am. Mus. Natl. Hist., 83, pp. 261-2